evices sometimes it is mistakenly called fast SCSI bit fast SCSI requires a SCSI software driver and SCSI electronics but can still use the SCSI Wide bit and bit SCSI require a different SCSI port electronics and software driver from SCSI Which makes them more expensive than other SCSI interfaces Mac SCSI asynchronous SCSI built in standard since the Even though Apple developed some specifications for SCSI controlers the OS SCSI Manager needs to be rewritten to take full advantage of the features of both SCSI As a result present SCSI Macs use bit SCSI as a fast asynchronous SCSI Presently Quadras are the only Macs with a SCSI controller chip built in Digital Review Oct though they lack some other parts of the hardware like the wide SCSI port Since other Macs require a NuBus card to use SCSI older NuBus Macs had a bottleneck due to the speed of the NuBus and Rumor some Cyclone Macs June will come with a wide fast SCSI port standard and have a rewritten OS SCSI IBM SCSI SCSI is not too wide spread yet generally not bundled with systems except as add on EISA and VESA Local Bus adapters avalable Like the Mac bit SCSI is used as a very fast SCSI by most controllers out Unlike the Mac IBM has no exact SCSI controller specifications which results in added incompatibilities for Mac Memory expansion with a few exceptions the Mac has used non parity pin bit SIMM memory expansion since the While pin bit parity SIMMs could be used in these Macs only special IIcis could make use of the parity feature By convension both SIMM types are called pin SIMMs The IIfx used pin parity The LC III and all use a new pin SIMM that is accessable by bits at a time and is used in The Mac does a complete memory check at startup by writing reading every memory location if something is seriously wrong with a SIMM the Mac will not boot and give a sound chord indicating what the problem Since Macs made before Feb managed memory baced on data path SIMMs had to be installed in pairs bit or in sets of bit The Centris and Quadra eliminate this with a new memory management setup that allows memory to be upgraded one SIMM at a If the SIMMs are the same size are used then the memory is 'interleaved' across the two SIMMs resulting in a performance boost on RAM access MacWorld Apr Printers ADBs and modems built in interfaces Monitor interface and sound input built in on most present PDS Available in SE all present non Powerbook bit SE Portable LC LC II Classic line and Operates at CPU's Maximum through put data path in bytes CPU's MHz s s Standardized with the LC and bus With an adapter one NuBus card can be used in IIsi and Problem some cards have timing dependency which slows through put NuBus Mac II bit MHz bus clock to transaction bus cycle ratio and contiguous hand shake transactions at s theoretical peak Built in on all Modular Macs except the LC series and Performa The SE could be adapted to use this and there was even a Mac Plus SCSI Supports every possible expansion from CPU to Ethernet to NuBus NuBus Mac II back bus clock avg throughput s burst mode Future card designs will be instead of the old QuickRing A peer to peer bus used in parallel with NuBus Apple's VLBus Architecture is identical to that of VLBus Byte Burst mode s Byte In CPU expansion handled either through the PDS or the Unlike PDS Nubus CPU cards example Radius Rocket allow use of multiple processors at the same This is like having two or more Macs in the same box able to dual task or joinly process depending on the card or software involved Each NuBus card needs its own memory but most NuBus cards of this type come with RAM SIMMs on the card standard IBM Memory expansion parity SIMMs non parity SIMMs some newer models do a Mac like SIMM memory check or a dozen or so different types of memory HD Interfaces limited to hard drives by design or lack of development MFM Modified Frequency Modulation RLL Run Length Limited only used with smaller hard IDE Integrated Device Electronics Asynchronous s max