point numbers are bits with a hardware FPU bits when The way they are handled is dependent on the coding of whatever compiler or assembler was used for a On older DOS complilers exceptions could cause program aborts and would abort to the DOS prompt at the point where they Most present compilers handle this Result there is little consistent handling of numbers between DOS Windows and OS programs nor between programs for just one Networking Includes printing WYSIWYG printing can be a problem with either Mac of IBM machines especially if one sends TrueType fonts to a older style PostScript Mac Hardware Built in LocalTalk network port and a built in printer LocalTalk has moderate speeds Kb s requires special connectors for each machine and up and can be run off of either the printer port to include very old macs or the network port standard today Built in Ethernet is becoming common but many older Macs require a PDS or Nubus card at about for each These cards provide three connectors and transceivers thick thin and for The Macintosh Quadra family and some Centris models includes Ethernet interface on motherboard with transceivers TokenRing has been a network option since Software AppleTalk the suite of protocols standard with Mac OS which can use variety of media AppleShare client software included with the OS as well and can connect to file servers such as Novell Netware Open Banyan Vines DEC Pathworks Apple's AppleShare servers System File Sharing machines and AFP servers running on variety of UNIX MacTCP allows typical TCP IP communications telnet ftp NFS rlogin A later version will have Unix X Open Transport Interface XTI built in by the end of MacWeek Third party software to connect to NFS DEC Pathworks provides DECnet Peer to peer file sharing software built in to System See OS section Full server software is Printing requires connection of the printer and the printer being selected in the Changing printers is by selecting a different name in the The same is true